Fires.

A fire is a deadly flame planted on a tile that kills the player the instant they touch it. Unlike most traps, a fire deals no gradual damage and can't be blocked or worn down — stepping onto its tile ends the run and brings up the death prompt. What makes a fire dangerous beyond a fixed hazard is that it can hunt: once the player comes within its sight, a fire can be set to chase them across the map, creeping one tile closer every interval until it catches them or they put a wall between themselves and it.

How a fire works.

A fire burns on a single tile, looping its fire sound from that spot so the player can hear where it is. Touching that exact tile is fatal at any time — armed or not, moving or still — so a fire is always something to route around.

A fire also has a seeing range on each axis and a set of move-axis switches. While the player stays outside the seeing range, the fire sits where it was placed. The moment the player steps within range on every axis, the fire notices them and, from then on, homes toward them along whichever axes it's allowed to move on, advancing one tile every interval. Once a fire has noticed the player it stays locked on, so the only ways to survive a moving fire are to outrun it or to break its path with a wall or other obstacle. A fire with no move axes switched on never moves — it's a stationary flame that only kills if the player walks into it. On 3d maps the fire can also track and be tracked through height.

Fire fields.

The fire form takes the following:

Coordinates. An x and a y (and a z on 3d maps) — the tile the fire burns on.

X seeing range. How far along the x axis the fire can notice the player. Defaults to the map's full width.
Y seeing range. How far along the y axis the fire can notice the player. Defaults to the map's full depth.
Z seeing range. On 3d maps, how far along the height axis the fire can notice the player. Defaults to the map's full height.

Speed. The number of milliseconds between each step the fire takes while chasing, so a smaller number is a faster fire.

Fire sound (a folder name from the fire sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the burning loop and the hit clip played when the fire catches the player. Pick none for a silent fire.

Move on x axis (checkbox). When checked, the fire moves toward the player along the x axis once it notices them.
Move on y axis (checkbox). When checked, the fire moves toward the player along the y axis once it notices them.
Move on z axis (checkbox). On 3d maps, when checked, the fire moves toward the player through height once it notices them.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the fire sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the highlighted theme's hit clip, and hold control and press L to hear its burning loop.

Authoring fires by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a fire on a 2d or topdown map is written as fire x y xrange yrange speed firetype movex movey, where movex and movey are the literal words true or false. On a 3d map a z follows the y, a z range follows the y range, and a third move flag follows the others: fire x y z xrange yrange zrange speed firetype movex movey movez. The ranges and speed are numbers, and the fire sound must match a fire sounds folder name or the word none.
